07 Plots

Plotting is probably one of the most fun things to do in R, because you get a lot of “visual feedback” - if your code is correct, you are rewarded with a nice plot. While base R has a plotting function, the tidyverse’s ggplot2 is a much more advanced package for plotting. It has helped R to achieve its reputation as a great tool for data visualisation. ggplot2 is based on the “Grammar of Graphics” by Leland Wilkinson, a framework for good data visualisation in data science.

Call other scripts

First, we need some data. If the data from previous exercises is still in your environment, use this opportunity to clear your workspace using rm(list = ls()). We want to start with a clean slate. However, the work we did in the previous data wrangling script should not go to waste. Luckily, we can “call” other scripts from within the script we are currently working in. That means, we could run 06_data_wrangling.Rmd where all of the data cleaning was done, and would end up with a cleaned version of our nerd data. In fact, it’s good practice to distribute your code across several scripts so you know where to find what. The preprocessing could e.g. go into one script, the analysis into another one and then you could have a separate script for plots or tables.

However, 06_data_wrangling.Rmd does not only contain the code to clean the nerd data, but much more other code that we don’t need right now. It is also an R Markdown file, and we don’t want to render the entire file into an html. At this point, we will use a “normal” R script that contains nothing but the code that cleans our nerd data. Unlike an .Rmd file, it will not create a nice document with descriptions and results - it will simply run the preprocessing in the background.

I put all the preprocessing we did in the previous exercise into a script called "nerd_preprocessing.R" that is lying in this folder. Open it and take a look at what’s happening at each step in the script.

Before we run our preprocessing script, we still need to load the libraries we want to use. We could also load our libraries in the preprocessing script, but then it’s less obvious which libraries we are using, because they are “hidden” in a different script. I like to list all of my libraries at the top of in the main document.

library(tidyverse)

We can call other scripts using the function source(). It takes the path to the file you would like to run as it’s first argument.

# Read in data and preprocess it
nerd <- read.csv("exercises_solutions/data_sets/nerd_data_short.csv", sep = "\t")
source("exercises_solutions/nerd_preprocessing.R")

Simple plots

One basic plot that you will frequently need is a histogram. It’s a good way to quickly inspect the distribution of your data. Below, you see how a simple histogram for the participant age works.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

The concept is pretty simple: We pipe our data, nerd_red into the ggplot() function. Within the function, we use the aes() function, which stands for “aesthetics”. The aesthetic function is used to tell ggplot() all the information that is related to the data (as opposed to things that have nothing to do with the data, e.g. overall plot colour). It will make more sense once we see which things belong into aes() and which things belong outside of it. Unsurprisingly, the argument x is what we want to put on the x-axis, which is the age of our participants in this case. Lastly, we tell ggplot() to make a histogram from our data. ggplot2 uses different “geoms”, which you can imagine as different “geometric” plot shapes. Here, we use a geom called geom_histogram. Other geoms are for example geom_point, geom_bar or geom_boxplot. You can probably guess what they do. Note that we don’t use a pipe to add the histogram, but a plus sign. That is because ggplot() works with “layers”. It’s a bit like using PowerPoint: When you created a slide, some elements are behind/in front of each other. In ggplot2, it’s the same principle. Here, we already use two layers: The plot background as first layer (created by the ggplot() function), and then our histogram on top of that.

To get a feeling for how layers in a plot work, we’ll create the layers from the previous plot one by one. As soon as we pipe our data into the ggplot() function, the background of a plot is drawn, even though we don’t plot any data:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot()

If we additionally tell it that age will go on the x-axis, ggplot() will draw an axis for is, because it now knows the scale of the data. Because it doesn’t know which information will go on the y-axis, no y-axis is created. There is also no data that get’s plotted, because ggplot() doesn’t know how in which form to plot it (as histogram? as scatter plot?).

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age))

In our final histogram, you probably noted the warning message “stat_bin() using bins = 30. Pick better value with binwidth.” It tells us that our histogram used a default for the width of the bars (bins) in our histogram, but it might be better to pick a different one.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

1.1) Use the bins argument in geom_histogram() to try out different bin widths.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 40)

Let’s try another geom - geom_point, which will give us a scatter plot. It requires information on the x and y axis. (In our previous example, geom_histogram automatically calculated what to put on the y-axis.) Here is an example:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point()

When we think about scatter plots, we usually think about regression lines. How about adding a line to the data, indicating how age and nerd score are associated with each other? The corresponding geom is called geom_smooth.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth()
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

The default method for geom_smooth, as R informs us, is “loess”. It “[fits] a polynomial surface determined by one or more numerical predictors, using local fitting.” (Run?loess in the console for more information.) You see that it does not produce a straight line - if we want a plain linear regression, we have to set the argument method to "lm". With the argument se = FALSE we can get rid of the grey confidence interval around the data.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

1.2) Use geom_boxplot() to plot participants’ marital status on the x axis, and the age on the y axis.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = married, y = age)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

1.3) Create a scatter plot that displays the relationship between the nerdy question and the nerd_score.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerdy, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point()

Building plots

It is worth pointing out that you can

  1. save plots into variables just like anything else and
  2. add layers to existing plots that are stored in variables.

For example, we could save the first layer of our plot in a variable:

my_scatter_plot <- 
  nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score))

… which we can then use to call the plot:

my_scatter_plot

We can then simply add layers to the existing plot like this:

my_scatter_plot +
  geom_point()

This leaves the original plot intact. I didn’t overwrite my_scatter_plot, so it is unchanged:

my_scatter_plot

Building plots in separate steps like this can have advantages, for example when you want to have some structure in your code (e.g., first create your basic plot, and fine tune its appearance in a different step), or if you are building several similar plots with the same underlying structure. During this workshop, however, I will mostly avoid building plots like this. This has the advantage that whenever you see a plot, you will see the entire code that was used to create it. You won’t have to look for other layers that are “hidden” in different variables, which makes it easier to miss parts of a plot.

Adding aesthetics

It is very easy to split our data into different subgroups in our plot. For example, we could examine what the relationship between age and nerd score looks like as a function of gender. We can use a different colour for each group in gender by using the colour argument inside of aes() (both colour and color will work).

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(aes(colour = gender)) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Note how colour worked on both geom_point and geom_smooth.

3.1) Create a more complex version of the plot from 1.2). Use geom_boxplot() to plot participants’ marital status on the x axis, and the age on the y axis. Colour the boxplots based on gender.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = married, y = age, colour = gender)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

3.2) In the plot from 3.1), rename the argument colour to fill. What’s the difference?

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = married, y = age, fill = gender)) + 
  geom_boxplot()

3.3) Create a scatter plot with nerd_score and age. Use the argument shape within aes() to group the data by marital status. Additionally, colour the data by marital status.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerd_score, y = age, shape = married, colour = married)) +
  geom_point()

3.4) Create a scatter plot with nerd_score and age. Try using the argument size = nerdy within aes(). What happens if you use colour instead of size (or maybe even both)? Tip: It’s a bit easier to see what’s going on when you only use the first 50 rows or so of nerd_red.

nerd_red[1:50, ] %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerd_score, y = age, size = nerdy, colour = nerdy)) +
  geom_point()

Customise your plot

There are still a lot of things we can improve in the plots we created so far. For example, because ggplot() uses the column names it finds in the data, the y-axis in this plot is labelled with “nerd_score”.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point()

We can change the axis label using the function labs().

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(y = "sum score nerdiness questionnaire")

4.1) labs() can also change other labels of your plot. Run ?labs and read the description of the function to find out which other labels it can change. Try all of them (except for alt and alt_insight - these only work for web-pages).

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(
    title = "This is my title",
    subtitle = "I am a subtitle",
    caption = "Caption America",
    tag = "This is a tag",
    y = "sum score nerdiness questionnaire",
    x = "x axis title"
  )

The legend would look better if it was at the top of our plot. In general, many things about our plot’s appearance can be controlled using the theme() function, such as like font sizes, what the grid lines and axes look like and much, much more.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(y = "sum score nerdiness questionnaire") +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

You can see all the different options of theme() by taking a look at ?theme. Because there are so many things you can change, the options are a bit overwhelming. I normally prefer the web version of the documentation of theme(), because it’s easier to read.

Speaking of themes, the grey background with the white grid is the default theme ggplot2 is very famous for. However, it is certainly not the most beautiful and modern plot appearance anymore. We could set up a custom theme by manually changing all the things we don’t like about the current theme using the theme() function, but we can also use a different pre-defined theme. You can find a list of themes here.

Adding one of these themes works like this:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(y = "sum score nerdiness questionnaire") +
  theme_classic() + # change theme
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Note that we have to put in theme(legend.position = "top") after theme_classic(). That is because theme_classic() has a predefined position for the legend (at the right side of the plot). If we use theme_classic() after theme(legend.position = "top"), it will overwrite the legend position we previously set:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(y = "sum score nerdiness questionnaire") +
  theme(legend.position = "top") + # is overwritten by the theme
  theme_classic() # overwrites the previous setting

4.2) Try a different theme!

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = gender)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(y = "sum score nerdiness questionnaire") +
  theme_dark() +
  theme(legend.position = "top")

Lastly, let’s change the steps on the x and y axis. For this task, the function seq() comes in handy, which generates a sequence of numbers. The arguments it takes are where the sequence begins, where it ends and how big the steps in between should be:

# A sequence from 1 - 10 in steps of 2
seq(1, 10, 2)
## [1] 1 3 5 7 9

It is also possible not to give a step size, but the number of steps (i.e. the length of the output) instead:

seq(1, 10, length.out = 3)
## [1]  1.0  5.5 10.0

Now we can use seq() to adjust our x axis like this:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerd_score, y = age)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 130, 10))

4.3) You can probably guess what the function for adjusting the y axis is called like. Use it to change the steps on the y-axis.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerd_score, y = age)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 130, 10)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(10, 100, 10))

Note that the argument breaks only controls the size of the steps on an axis, but not the limits. In this example, we used breaks from 0 - 200, but the last label that is printed is 130.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerd_score, y = age)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 200, 10))

4.4) You can control the limits of an axis using the argument limits inside of scale_x_continuous(). It requires a vector with two elements as input: The first element controls the lower limit of the axis, the second element controls the upper limit of the axis. Try different limits for the x and y axis!

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = nerd_score, y = age)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 130, 10)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(20, 100, 10), limits = c(10, 100))

Beyond aes()

So far, when we used different colours our shapes to plot our data, we did that inside of the aes() function. You might have wondered why we even need to wrap our code in an additional function. Here’s why: When we put something inside the aes() function, we are using the underlying data to control our plot’s appearance. When we use the same argument outside of aes(), we are controlling our plot’s appearance irrespective of the underlying data.

For example, here we colour the points in our scatter plot depending on our participants’ marital status.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = married)) +
  geom_point()

Used outside of aes(), the colour argument affects all data points.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(colour = "dark green")

We can refer to the colour that we want by name (i.e. "black", or "dark red" - find a full list here), but can also use hex codes (e.g. "#2d82b7").

Note that we have to use colour inside of geom_point - it won’t work in the ggplot() function:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score), colour = "green") +
  geom_point()

It helps to understand the difference between colour inside vs. outside of aes() if we use colour = "green" inside of aes():

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score, colour = "blue")) +
  geom_point()

4.5) Optional: Take a moment to think about what is going on here.

4.6) Try the arguments size and alpha outside of aes(). If you want to, you can use other geoms and try out how these arguments affect them.

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(size = 4, alpha = .3, colour = "#118EA7")

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(nerdy), y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_boxplot(
    size = 1, colour = "#118EA7", fill = "#ff449d", alpha = .2
  )

Custom colours

Outside of aes(), we can simply tell R which colours or shapes to use. But if we e.g. colour our data inside of aes(), we get default colours. Here’s how we change them:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = nerd_score, fill = married)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("yellow", "pink", "purple")) + # custom colours
  geom_boxplot()

Using the values argument in scale_fill_manual(), we can provide R with a vector of custom colours we want to use in our plot. Note that we need to specify a value for each colour in the plot, i.e. if there are three different colours (groups) in the plot, we need to provide three colour values.

Changing other aesthetics works in the same way - the functions are just called slightly different. E.g. there’s scale_colour_manual() or scale_shape_manual().

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = gender, y = nerd_score, fill = married, colour = married)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("yellow", "pink", "purple")) + # custom colours
  scale_colour_manual(values = c("pink", "purple", "yellow")) +
  geom_boxplot()

5.1) Create your own plot with custom aesthetics. Try out what happens if you change the order of the values in the vector.

Facets

We can also split our data into different facets, which creates plot panels based on groups in the data. Here is an example - the variable which the facets should be based on is provided after a little ~:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .4) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  facet_wrap(~ gender)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

You can also create facets based on two variables by specifying a variable on each side of the ~:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .4) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  facet_wrap(voted ~ gender)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

There is also the very similar facet_grid() function that basically does the same thing, but with a slightly different result:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .4) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  facet_grid(voted ~ gender)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

6.1) Create a plot with facets yourself. Try to additionally add some aesthetics that are based on the data (i.e. that work inside of aes()).

Optional

Earlier, we saw that fill controls the colour a geom (e.g. a boxplot) is filled with, while colour controls the colour of the outline. So, it seems odd that we use colour to control the filling of the points in a scatter plot. That is because by default, the scatter plot uses a shape (the points) that don’t have a filling. There are other shapes that have both a filling and a border. Compare the following examples:

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, colour = "red", fill = "green", shape = 20)

nerd_red %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = nerd_score)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, colour = "red", fill = "green", shape = 21)

There are several different shapes that we can use in our scatter plot, and we address them by different numbers using the shape argument. Here is a list of all available shapes. Shapes 21 - 25 respond to colour and fill.
